<subSubSection id="C30B85FEB165FFECFF05F8D7A518D3A4" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="415" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAED675B165FFECFF05F8D7A518D3A4" blockId="13.[151,1437,1586,2046]" lastBlockId="14.[151,1436,152,251]" lastPageId="14" lastPageNumber="415" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFF05F8D7A763D415" bold="true" box="[199,308,1840,1866]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Remarks</emphasis>
: According to 
<bibRefCitation id="EF80AB84B165FFEFFE15F8C8A4B8D416" author="Crosnier, A. &amp; Forest, J." box="[471,751,1839,1866]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" pagination="1 - 409" refId="ref18101" refString="Crosnier, A. &amp; Forest, J. (1973) Les crevettes profondes de l'Atlantique oriental tropical. Faune Tropicale, 19, 1 - 409." type="journal article" year="1973">Crosnier &amp; Forest (1973)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="EF80AB84B165FFEFFCE1F8C8A26BD416" author="Cardoso, I. A. &amp; Young, P. S." box="[803,1084,1838,1866]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref17500" refString="Cardoso, I. A. &amp; Young, P. S. (2005) Deep-sea Oplophoridae (Crustacea Caridea) from the southwestern Brazil. Zootaxa, 1031 (1), 1 - 76. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1031.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Cardoso &amp; Young (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, the closest species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C11ADF6B165FFEFFAF6F8C8A6A9D432" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Ephyrina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="benedicti">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFAF6F8C8A6A9D432" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Ephyrina benedicti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName id="4C11ADF6B165FFEFFEDDF8B3A407D432" authority="Stephensen, 1923" authorityName="Stephensen" authorityYear="1923" box="[287,592,1875,1901]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Ephyrina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFEDDF8B3A728D432" box="[287,383,1875,1901]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">E. bifida</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF80AB84B165FFEFFE45F8B4A407D432" author="Stephensen, K." box="[391,592,1875,1901]" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" pagination="1 - 85" refId="ref21251" refString="Stephensen, K. (1923) Decapoda-Macrura excl. Sergestidae. (Penaida, Pasiphaidae, Hoplophoridae, Nematocarcinida, Scyllarida, Eryonida, Nephropsida, Appendix). Report on the Danish Oceanographical Expeditions 1908 - 1910 to the Mediterranean and adjacent Seas, 2, 1 - 85." type="journal article" year="1923">Stephensen, 1923</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but these species differ from each other in the following way (character of 
<taxonomicName id="4C11ADF6B165FFEFFF55F89FA6AED4CE" authorityName="Stephensen" authorityYear="1923" box="[151,249,1911,1937]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Ephyrina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifida">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFF55F89FA6AED4CE" box="[151,249,1911,1937]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">E. bifida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in parentheses): abdominal somite 3 with a simple dorsal tooth (
<figureCitation id="132ACAF0B165FFEFFC1EF890A215D4CE" box="[988,1090,1911,1937]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1480,1505]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,722,1469]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,718,1469]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 13. Ephyrina benedicti Smith, 1885. A. Female, lateral view. B. Telson, dorsal view. C. Abdomen, with somites 1–6 in dorsal view. (MOUPE: 19.417). Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3239785/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 13B</figureCitation>
) (
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFB9EF89FA224D4CE" box="[1116,1139,1912,1937]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">vs</emphasis>
abdominal somite 3 present a bifid dorsal tooth); telson with 22–27 dorsolateral spines (
<figureCitation id="132ACAF0B165FFEFFCA4F87CA59DD4EA" box="[870,970,1947,1973]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1480,1505]" captionTargetBox="[156,1429,722,1469]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,718,1469]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 13. Ephyrina benedicti Smith, 1885. A. Female, lateral view. B. Telson, dorsal view. C. Abdomen, with somites 1–6 in dorsal view. (MOUPE: 19.417). Scale bar = 1 cm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3239785/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 13C</figureCitation>
) (
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFC26F87BA5ACD4EA" box="[996,1019,1948,1973]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">vs</emphasis>
telson with 4–7 dorsolateral spines). 
<taxonomicName id="4C11ADF6B165FFEFFF55F858A727D486" box="[151,368,1983,2009]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Ephyrina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="414" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="benedicti">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B165FFEFFF55F858A727D486" box="[151,368,1983,2009]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Ephyrina benedicti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a cosmopolitan distribution, but despite its wide occurrence in all oceans (
<figureCitation id="132ACAF0B165FFEFFAC7F858A30DD486" box="[1285,1370,1983,2009]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="14.[151,246,774,799]" captionTargetBox="[321,1282,303,737]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[242,1282,270,737]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 14. Global geographic distribution of Ephyrina benedicti Smith, 1885. Black circles = previous records; star = new record." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3239787/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="414">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), few records were made in Western Atlantic, especially in Southwest Atlantic, being the first report of genus from Bra- zilian waters made by 
<bibRefCitation id="EF80AB84B166FFECFE56FF7EA4E5D3EC" author="Cardoso, I. A. &amp; Young, P. S." box="[404,690,152,179]" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref17500" refString="Cardoso, I. A. &amp; Young, P. S. (2005) Deep-sea Oplophoridae (Crustacea Caridea) from the southwestern Brazil. Zootaxa, 1031 (1), 1 - 76. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1031.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Cardoso &amp; Young (2005)</bibRefCitation>
, with specimens collected in Campos Basin in States of 
<collectingRegion id="49D51897B166FFECFAE9FF7EA33BD3EC" box="[1323,1388,153,179]" country="Brazil" name="Bahia" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Bahia</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="49D51897B166FFECFF55FF5AA76DD388" box="[151,314,189,215]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
. We provide herein the second report of the species 
<taxonomicName id="4C11ADF6B166FFECFC40FF59A2C4D388" authority="in Brazilian" authorityName="in Brazilian" box="[898,1171,189,215]" class="Malacostraca" family="Oplophoridae" genus="Ephyrina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="14" pageNumber="415" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="benedicti">
<emphasis id="B9650A67B166FFECFC40FF59A25FD388" box="[898,1032,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">E. benedicti</emphasis>
in Brazilian
</taxonomicName>
waters highlighting the first observation in seamounts located in Northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F30696E5B166FFECFCC1FF06A51CD3A4" box="[771,843,225,251]" name="Brazil" pageId="14" pageNumber="415">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
